           <div class="thumbcaption">

            Taranaki <a href="/wiki/Andesite" title="Andesite">andesite</a> (red shading) in centre of map. The surrounding debris and <a href="/wiki/Lahar" title="Lahar">lahar</a> fields are not shown although they include the green forested area on the map that surround Mount Taranaki and the <a href="/wiki/Pouakai_Range" title="Pouakai Range">Pouakai Range</a> and have reached the sea in all directions on the Taranaki peninsular except where blocked by the Pouakai Range. The key to the other volcanics that are shown with panning is <a href="/wiki/Basalt" title="Basalt">basalt</a> - brown, <a href="/wiki/Monogenetic_volcanic_field" title="Monogenetic volcanic field">monogenetic</a> basalts - dark brown, undifferentiated basalts of the Tangihua Complex in Northland Allochthon - light brown, arc basalts - deep orange brown, arc ring basalts -orange brown, <a href="/wiki/Dacite" title="Dacite">dacite</a> - purple, <a href="/wiki/Andesite" title="Andesite">andesite</a> - red, basaltic andesite`- light red, <a href="/wiki/Rhyolite" title="Rhyolite">rhyolite</a> - violet , <a href="/wiki/Ignimbrite" title="Ignimbrite">ignimbrite</a> (lighter shades of violet), and <a href="/wiki/Intrusive_rock" title="Intrusive rock">plutonic</a> - gray.

           </div>

         </div> 

         <p><b>Mount Taranaki</b> (<a href="/wiki/M%C4%81ori_language" title="MƒÅori language">MƒÅori</a>: <i lang="mi">Taranaki Maunga</i>; is a dormant <a href="/wiki/Stratovolcano" title="Stratovolcano">stratovolcano</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Taranaki" title="Taranaki">Taranaki</a> region on the west coast of New Zealand's <a href="/wiki/North_Island" title="North Island">North Island</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> At 2,518 metres (8,261 ft), it is the second highest mountain in the North Island, after <a href="/wiki/Mount_Ruapehu" title="Mount Ruapehu">Mount Ruapehu</a>. It has a secondary cone, Fanthams Peak (<a href="/wiki/M%C4%81ori_language" title="MƒÅori language">MƒÅori</a>: <i lang="mi">Panitahi</i>), 1,966 metres (6,450 ft), on its south side.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> </p> 

         <meta property="mw:PageProp/toc"> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Name">Name</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=1" title="Edit section: Name">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 

         <p>The name <i>Taranaki</i> is from the <a href="/wiki/M%C4%81ori_language" title="MƒÅori language">MƒÅori language</a>. It comes from Ruataranaki, ancestor of the local Taranaki <a href="/wiki/Iwi" title="Iwi">iwi</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> The MƒÅori word <i>tara</i> means mountain peak, and <i>naki</i> may come from <i>ngaki</i>, meaning "clear of vegetation."<sup id="cite_ref-Reed_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Reed-8">[8]</a></sup> It was also named <span title="MƒÅori-language text"><i lang="mi">Pukehaupapa</i></span> ("ice mountain") and <span title="MƒÅori-language text"><i lang="mi">Pukeonaki</i></span> ("hill of Naki") by iwi who lived in the region in "ancient times".<sup id="cite_ref-Reed_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Reed-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-TeAra_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TeAra-9">[9]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> </p>

         <p><a href="/wiki/James_Cook" title="James Cook">Captain Cook</a> named it Mount Egmont on 11 January 1770<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup> after <a href="/wiki/John_Perceval,_2nd_Earl_of_Egmont" title="John Perceval, 2nd Earl of Egmont">John Perceval, 2nd Earl of Egmont</a>, a former <a href="/wiki/First_Lord_of_the_Admiralty" title="First Lord of the Admiralty">First Lord of the Admiralty</a> who had supported the concept of an oceanic search for <i><a href="/wiki/Terra_Australis_Incognita" class="mw-redirect" title="Terra Australis Incognita">Terra Australis Incognita</a></i>. Cook described it as "of a prodigious height and its top cover'd with everlasting snow," surrounded by a "flat country ... which afforded a very good aspect, being clothed with wood and <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/verdure" class="extiw" title="wikt:verdure">verdure</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> </p>

         <p>When the French explorer <a href="/wiki/Marc-Joseph_Marion_du_Fresne" title="Marc-Joseph Marion du Fresne">Marc-Joseph Marion du Fresne</a> saw the mountain on 25 March 1772 he named it <i>Pic Mascarin</i>. He was unaware of Cook's earlier visit.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> </p>

         <p>It appeared as Mount Egmont on maps until 29 May 1986, when the name officially became "Mount Taranaki or Mount Egmont"<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> following a decision by the Minister of Lands.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> The Egmont name still applies to the national park that surrounds the peak and geologists still refer to the peak as the Egmont Volcano.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> </p>

         <p>As part of the <a href="/wiki/Treaty_of_Waitangi_claims_and_settlements" title="Treaty of Waitangi claims and settlements">treaty settlement</a> with <a href="/wiki/Taranaki_(iwi)" title="Taranaki (iwi)">NgƒÅ Iwi o Taranaki</a> the mountain will be officially named <i>Taranaki Maunga</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> The settlement was completed on 31 March 2023.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Geology">Geology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=2" title="Edit section: Geology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 

         <p>It is situated in the sedmentary <a href="/wiki/Taranaki_Basin" title="Taranaki Basin">Taranaki Basin</a> and is part of the Taranaki Volcanic Lineament which has had a 30‚ÄÖmm/yr north to south migration over the last 1.75 million years.<sup id="cite_ref-Cronin2021_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cronin2021-20">[20]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Volcanic_activity">Volcanic activity</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=3" title="Edit section: Volcanic activity">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 

         <p>Taranaki is geologically young, having commenced activity approximately 135,000 years ago. The most recent volcanic activity was the production of a lava dome in the crater and its collapse down the side of the mountain in the 1850s or 1860s.<sup id="cite_ref-pukeariki_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pukeariki-21">[21]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> Between 1755 and 1800, an eruption sent a <a href="/wiki/Pyroclastic_flow" title="Pyroclastic flow">pyroclastic flow</a> down the mountain's northeast flanks,<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> and a moderate ash eruption occurred about 1755, of the size of <a href="/wiki/Mount_Ruapehu" title="Mount Ruapehu">Ruapehu</a>'s activity in 1995/1996. The last major eruption occurred around 1655. Recent research has shown that over the last 9,000 years minor eruptions have occurred roughly every 90 years on average, with major eruptions every 500 years.<sup id="cite_ref-Price1999_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Price1999-24">[24]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Hazards">Hazards</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=4" title="Edit section: Hazards">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 

         <div class="thumb tright">

          <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">

           <a href="/wiki/File:Lahars_at_Mt_Taranaki_New_Zealand.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Lahars_at_Mt_Taranaki_New_Zealand.jpg/220px-Lahars_at_Mt_Taranaki_New_Zealand.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="148" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Lahars_at_Mt_Taranaki_New_Zealand.jpg/330px-Lahars_at_Mt_Taranaki_New_Zealand.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Lahars_at_Mt_Taranaki_New_Zealand.jpg/440px-Lahars_at_Mt_Taranaki_New_Zealand.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1375"></a> 

           <div class="thumbcaption">

            <div class="magnify">

             <a href="/wiki/File:Lahars_at_Mt_Taranaki_New_Zealand.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>

            </div>Remains from a lahar at Taranaki

           </div>

          </div>

         </div> 

         <p>Taranaki is unusual in that it has experienced at least five of its major eruptions by the method of cone collapse. Few volcanoes have undergone more than one cone collapse. The vast volume of material involved in these collapses is reflected in the extensive ring plain<sup id="cite_ref-Price1999_24-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Price1999-24">[24]</a></sup> surrounding the volcano. There is also evidence of <a href="/wiki/Lahar" title="Lahar">lahars</a> being a common result of eruption. The major collapse cycles have a potential maximum size of collapse of 7.9 km<sup>3</sup> (1.9 cu mi) every 30,000 to 35,000 years. Another major collapse is expected to occur with 16,200 years.<sup id="cite_ref-Cronin2021_20-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cronin2021-20">[20]</a></sup> </p>

         <p>Much of the region is at risk from lahars, which have reached as far as the coast. A volcanic event is not necessary for a lahar: even earthquakes combined with heavy rain or snow could dislodge vast quantities of unstable layers resting on steep slopes. Many farmers live in the paths of such possible destructive events. </p>

         <p>Although volcanic eruptions are notoriously chaotic in their frequency, some scientists warn that a large eruption is "overdue". Research from <a href="/wiki/Massey_University" title="Massey University">Massey University</a> indicates that significant seismic activity from the local faults is likely again in the next 50 years and such might be permissive to an eruption. What ever in the next 50 years, the probability of at least one eruption is between 33% and 42%.<sup id="cite_ref-Cronin2021_20-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Cronin2021-20">[20]</a></sup> Prevailing winds would probably blow ash east, covering much of the North Island, and disrupting air routes, power transmission lines and local water supplies.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Older_volcanoes_in_the_area">Older volcanoes in the area</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=5" title="Edit section: Older volcanoes in the area">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 

         <div class="thumb tright">

          <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">

           <a href="/wiki/File:Mount_Taranaki,_New_Zealand.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Mount_Taranaki%2C_New_Zealand.jpg/220px-Mount_Taranaki%2C_New_Zealand.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Mount_Taranaki%2C_New_Zealand.jpg/330px-Mount_Taranaki%2C_New_Zealand.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Mount_Taranaki%2C_New_Zealand.jpg/440px-Mount_Taranaki%2C_New_Zealand.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5616" data-file-height="3744"></a> 

           <div class="thumbcaption">

            <div class="magnify">

             <a href="/wiki/File:Mount_Taranaki,_New_Zealand.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>

            </div>From <a href="/wiki/New_Plymouth" title="New Plymouth">New Plymouth</a>

           </div>

          </div>

         </div> 

         <p>Mount Taranaki is one of four closely associated <a href="/wiki/Quaternary" title="Quaternary">Quaternary</a> volcanoes in Taranaki province that have erupted from <a href="/wiki/Andesite" title="Andesite">andesite</a> <a href="/wiki/Magma" title="Magma">magmas</a> that have not extensively assimilated enriched crust unlike the cone volcanos of the <a href="/wiki/North_Island_Volcanic_Plateau" title="North Island Volcanic Plateau">North Island Volcanic Plateau</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Price1999_24-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Price1999-24">[24]</a></sup> It sits on the remains of three older volcanic complexes that lie to the northwest. The <a href="/wiki/Indo-Australian_Plate" title="Indo-Australian Plate">Indo-Australian Plate</a> is slowly moving relative to the <a href="/wiki/Magma" title="Magma">magma</a> source that feeds these volcanoes. This trend is reflected in Fanthams Peak, the newer secondary cone on the southeast side of Taranaki and named after Fanny Fantham who was the first European woman to climb the peak in 1887.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> </p>

         <p>The oldest volcanic remnants consist of a series of lava plugs: Paritutu Rock (156 metres), which forms part of <a href="/wiki/New_Plymouth" title="New Plymouth">New Plymouth</a>'s harbour, and the <a href="/wiki/Sugar_Loaf_Islands" title="Sugar Loaf Islands">Sugar Loaf Islands</a> close offshore. These have been dated at 1.75 million years. </p>

         <p>On the coast, 15 kilometres southwest of New Plymouth is the <a href="/wiki/Kaitake_Range" title="Kaitake Range">Kaitake Range</a> (682 metres), last active approximately 500,000 years ago. </p>

         <p>Nearest to Taranaki is the <a href="/wiki/Pouakai_Range" title="Pouakai Range">Pouakai Range</a>. Pouakai may have originated around the same time as Kaitake but remained active until about 240,000 years ago. Much of Pouakai's large ring plain was obliterated by the Egmont Volcano, the hills near Eltham being the only remnant to the south.<sup id="cite_ref-pukeariki_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pukeariki-21">[21]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h2><span id="M.C4.81ori_mythology"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="MƒÅori_mythology">MƒÅori mythology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=6" title="Edit section: MƒÅori mythology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 

         <div class="thumb tright">

          <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">

           <a href="/wiki/File:Taranaki_daybreak.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Taranaki_daybreak.jpg/220px-Taranaki_daybreak.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Taranaki_daybreak.jpg/330px-Taranaki_daybreak.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Taranaki_daybreak.jpg/440px-Taranaki_daybreak.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3872" data-file-height="2592"></a> 

           <div class="thumbcaption">

            <div class="magnify">

             <a href="/wiki/File:Taranaki_daybreak.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>

            </div>Taranaki at daybreak 2008

           </div>

          </div>

         </div> 

         <p>According to MƒÅori mythology,<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]</a></sup> Taranaki once resided in the middle of the North Island, with all the other New Zealand volcanoes. The beautiful <a href="/wiki/Pihanga" title="Pihanga">Pihanga</a> was coveted by all the mountains, and a great battle broke out between them. <a href="/wiki/Mount_Tongariro" title="Mount Tongariro">Tongariro</a> eventually won the day,<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> inflicted great wounds on the side of Taranaki, and causing him to flee. Taranaki headed westwards, following Te Toka a Rahotu (the Rock of <a href="/wiki/Rahotu" title="Rahotu">Rahotu</a>) and forming the deep gorges of the <a href="/wiki/Whanganui_River" title="Whanganui River">Whanganui River</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup> paused for a while, creating the depression that formed the Te Ngaere swamp, then heading north. Further progress was blocked by the <a href="/wiki/Pouakai_Range" title="Pouakai Range">Pouakai Ranges</a>, and as the sun came up Taranaki became petrified in his current location. When Taranaki conceals himself with rainclouds, he is said to be crying for his lost love, and during spectacular sunsets, he is said to be displaying himself to her.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> In turn, Tongariro's eruptions are said to be a warning to Taranaki not to return. </p> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=7" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 

         <div class="thumb tright">

          <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">

           <a href="/wiki/File:Mount_Taranaki_1896_SLNSW_FL10386956.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Mount_Taranaki_1896_SLNSW_FL10386956.jpg/220px-Mount_Taranaki_1896_SLNSW_FL10386956.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="168" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Mount_Taranaki_1896_SLNSW_FL10386956.jpg/330px-Mount_Taranaki_1896_SLNSW_FL10386956.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Mount_Taranaki_1896_SLNSW_FL10386956.jpg/440px-Mount_Taranaki_1896_SLNSW_FL10386956.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3468" data-file-height="2647"></a> 

           <div class="thumbcaption">

            <div class="magnify">

             <a href="/wiki/File:Mount_Taranaki_1896_SLNSW_FL10386956.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>

            </div>Mount Taranaki (Mt Egmont), from Inglewood, New Zealand, 1896

           </div>

          </div>

         </div> 

         <div class="thumb tright">

          <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">

           <a href="/wiki/File:NEO_egmont_big.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/NEO_egmont_big.jpg/220px-NEO_egmont_big.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="204" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/NEO_egmont_big.jpg/330px-NEO_egmont_big.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/NEO_egmont_big.jpg/440px-NEO_egmont_big.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3560" data-file-height="3295"></a> 

           <div class="thumbcaption">

            <div class="magnify">

             <a href="/wiki/File:NEO_egmont_big.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>

            </div>NASA satellite photo of Taranaki. The forested area matches the national park boundary fairly closely.

           </div>

          </div>

         </div> 

         <p>In 1865 the mountain was <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_land_confiscations" title="New Zealand land confiscations">confiscated</a> from MƒÅori by the New Zealand Government under the powers of the New Zealand Settlements Act 1863, ostensibly as a means of establishing and maintaining peace amid the <a href="/wiki/Second_Taranaki_War" title="Second Taranaki War">Second Taranaki War</a>. The legislation was framed with the intention of seizing and dividing up the land of MƒÅori "in rebellion" and providing it as farmland for military settlers. In 1839 the mountain had been climbed by the Swiss trained doctor and naturalist <a href="/wiki/Ernst_Dieffenbach" title="Ernst Dieffenbach">Ernst Dieffenbach</a>. During his initial ascent, he identified the fast-flowing streams as being well suited to water driven mills. Dieffenbach was employed by the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Company" title="New Zealand Company">New Zealand Company</a> to advise on the potential of land he explored in the North Island in 1839‚Äì40.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title="Wikipedia:Verifiability"><span title="The citation is not specific enough to facilitate source verification (May 2014)">not specific enough to verify</span></a></i>]</sup> </p>

         <p>The mountain was returned to the people of Taranaki in 1978 by means of the Mount Egmont Vesting Act 1978, which vested it to the Taranaki Maori Trust Board. By means of the same Act, it was immediately passed back to the Government as a gift to the nation.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Waitangi_Tribunal" title="Waitangi Tribunal">Waitangi Tribunal</a>, in its 1996 report, Kaupapa Tuatahi,<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]</a></sup> observed: "We are unaware of the evidence that the <a href="/wiki/Hap%C5%AB" title="Hap≈´">hap≈´</a> agreed to this arrangement. Many who made submissions to us were adamant that most knew nothing of it." It cited a submission that suggested the political climate of 1975 was such that the board felt it was necessary to perform a gesture of goodwill designed to create a more favourable environment within which a monetary settlement could be negotiated. </p>

         <p>Because of its resemblance to <a href="/wiki/Mount_Fuji" title="Mount Fuji">Mount Fuji</a>, Taranaki provided the backdrop for the 2003 film <i><a href="/wiki/The_Last_Samurai" title="The Last Samurai">The Last Samurai</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-TeAra_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-TeAra-9">[9]</a></sup> </p>

         <p>In 2017, a record of understanding was signed between Taranaki iwi and the New Zealand government that will see the mountain become a legal personality.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">[34]</a></sup> It is the third geographic feature in the country to be granted a legal personality, after <a href="/wiki/Te_Urewera" title="Te Urewera">Te Urewera</a> and <a href="/wiki/Whanganui_River" title="Whanganui River">Whanganui River</a>. </p>

         <p>On 2 December 2019, an agreement between the crown and <a href="/w/index.php?title=Ng%C4%81_Iwi_o_Taranaki&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="NgƒÅ Iwi o Taranaki (page does not exist)">NgƒÅ Iwi o Taranaki</a> was announced that the mountain was to only be referred to as Taranaki Maunga. The national park will be renamed from <a href="/wiki/Egmont_National_Park" title="Egmont National Park">Egmont National Park</a> to Te Papakura o Taranaki.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup> The name change has not yet been ratified by the New Zealand Geographic Board.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">[36]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="National_park">National park</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=8" title="Edit section: National park">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 

         <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1033289096">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}</style>

         <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">

          Main article: <a href="/wiki/Egmont_National_Park" title="Egmont National Park">Egmont National Park</a>

         </div> 

         <p>In 1881, a circular area with a radius of six miles (9.6 km) from the summit was protected as a forest reserve. Areas encompassing the older volcanic remnants of Pouakai and Kaitake were later added to the reserve and in 1900 all this land was gazetted as Egmont National Park, the second <a href="/wiki/National_park" title="National park">national park</a> in New Zealand. There are parts of the national park where <a href="/wiki/Old-growth_forest" title="Old-growth forest">old-growth forests</a> are found.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">[37]</a></sup> With intensively-farmed dairy pasture right up to the park boundary, the change in vegetation is sharply delineated as a circular shape in satellite images.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Recreation">Recreation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=9" title="Edit section: Recreation">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 

         <div class="thumb tright">

          <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">

           <a href="/wiki/File:Pouakai_Track_3.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Pouakai_Track_3.jpg/220px-Pouakai_Track_3.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Pouakai_Track_3.jpg/330px-Pouakai_Track_3.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Pouakai_Track_3.jpg/440px-Pouakai_Track_3.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1536"></a> 

           <div class="thumbcaption">

            <div class="magnify">

             <a href="/wiki/File:Pouakai_Track_3.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>

            </div>Taranaki from the Pouakai Circuit tramping track

           </div>

          </div>

         </div> 

         <p>The Stratford Mountain Club operates the <a href="/wiki/Manganui" title="Manganui">Manganui skifield</a> on the eastern slope. Equipment access to the skifield is by <a href="/wiki/Zip_line" title="Zip line">flying fox</a> across the Manganui Gorge. </p>

         <p>The Taranaki Alpine Club maintains Tahurangi Lodge on the north slope of the mountain, next to the television tower. The lodge is frequently used as the base for public climbs to the summit held in the summer months. The various climbing and tramping clubs organize these public events and provide informal guides. </p>

         <p>Syme Hut is located near Fanthams Peak. It is maintained by the Department of Conservation and is available to trampers on a first come first served basis. </p>

         <p>For the average person, Taranaki would be considered a moderate mountain to climb. It takes a person with good fitness level a day to make the up-and-back climb. Weather on the mountain can change rapidly, which has caught inexperienced <a href="/wiki/Hiking" title="Hiking">trampers</a> and climbers unawares. As of 27 June 2017, 84 people have died on the mountain since records began in 1891, many having been caught by a sudden change in the weather. In terms of fatalities this mountain is the second most dangerous mountain in New Zealand after <a href="/wiki/Aoraki_/_Mount_Cook" title="Aoraki / Mount Cook">Aoraki / Mount Cook</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">[39]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">[40]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Gallery">Gallery</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=10" title="Edit section: Gallery">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Access">Access</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=11" title="Edit section: Access">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 

         <div class="thumb tright">

          <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">

           <a href="/wiki/File:Clouds_around_Mount_Taranaki.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Clouds_around_Mount_Taranaki.jpg/220px-Clouds_around_Mount_Taranaki.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="138" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Clouds_around_Mount_Taranaki.jpg/330px-Clouds_around_Mount_Taranaki.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Clouds_around_Mount_Taranaki.jpg/440px-Clouds_around_Mount_Taranaki.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1231" data-file-height="774"></a> 

           <div class="thumbcaption">

            <div class="magnify">

             <a href="/wiki/File:Clouds_around_Mount_Taranaki.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>

            </div>Aerial view of Mount Taranaki 2015

           </div>

          </div>

         </div> 

         <p>There are three roads leading part-way up the mountain. The highest is to East Egmont plateau, with a viewing platform and parking facilities for the skifield. It lies at the transition between subalpine scrub and alpine <a href="/wiki/Herbfield" title="Herbfield">herbfields</a>. </p>

         <p>There are park visitor centres at North Egmont and at Dawson Falls on the southeast side. </p>

         <p>The eastern side from Stratford leads to the Stratford Mountain House, and the ski field. </p>

         <p>There is no road access on the western side. However, a road winds for 10 km through native bush over the saddle between Pouakai and Kaitake. Near the top of this road is the renowned <a href="/wiki/Pukeiti_(gardens)" title="Pukeiti (gardens)">Pukeiti</a> Trust <a href="/wiki/Rhododendron" title="Rhododendron">rhododendron</a> garden.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (January 2010)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> </p> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Transmitter">Transmitter</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=12" title="Edit section: Transmitter">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 

         <p>The Mount Egmont transmitter is the main television and FM radio transmitter for the Taranaki region. It is located on the north-eastern slope of the mountain adjacent to Tahurangi Lodge. The first transmitter at the site was commissioned by the <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand_Broadcasting_Corporation" title="New Zealand Broadcasting Corporation">New Zealand Broadcasting Corporation</a> (NZBC) in 1966 to relay Wellington's WNTV1 channel (now part of <a href="/wiki/TVNZ_1" title="TVNZ 1">TVNZ 1</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">[41]</a></sup> </p> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=13" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

         </ul> 

         <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Mount_Taranaki&action=edit&section=14" title="Edit section: References">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
